05481nam a22005535i 9780822396703DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19981998ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223967037 a10.1515/97808223967032doi  a(DE-B1597)552159  a(OCoLC)913464171  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aLA227.4b.K65 1998 7aEDU0150002bisacsh04a378.732211 aKolodny, Annette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFailing the Future :bA Dean Looks at Higher Education in the Twenty-first Century /cAnnette Kolodny. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Personal Preface: Reflections on Five Years in a Dean's Office -- t1 Facing the Future: An Introduction -- t2 "60 Minutes" at the University of Arizona: The Polemic against Tenure -- t3 Raising Standards While Lowering Anxieties: Rethinking the Promotion and Tenure Process -- t4 Paying the Price of Antifeminist Intellectual Harassment -- t5 Creating the Family-Friendly Campus -- t6 Teaching and Learning in a World of Cognitive Diversity -- t7 Setting an Agenda for Change -- t8 Failing the Future; or, How to Commit National Suicide at the End of the Twentieth Century -- tA Closing Refrain: Reflections at a Graduation -- tAppendix 1. University of Arizona College of Humanities Promotion and Tenure Procedures -- tAppendix 2. Summary Checklist of Selected Family-Friendly Initiatives and Programs -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBoth revealing and compelling, Annette Kolodny's Failing the Future: A Dean Looks at Higher Education in the Twenty-first Century is drawn from the author's experience as a distinguished teacher, a prize-winning scholar of American literature, a feminist thinker, and an innovative administrator at a major public university. In chapters that range from the changing structure of the American family and its impact on both curriculum and university benefits policies to recommendations for overhauling the culture of decision making on campus, this former Dean of the College of Humanities at the University of Arizona explores the present state of higher education and offers a sobering view of what lies ahead.In this volume Kolodny explains the reasons for the financial crisis in higher education today and boldly addresses the challenges that remain ignored, including rising birthrates, changing demographics both on campus and across the country, the accelerating globalization of higher education and advanced research, and the necessity for greater interdisciplinarity in undergraduate education. Moreover, while sensitive to the complex burdens placed on faculty today, Kolodny nonetheless reveals how the professoriate has allowed itself to become vulnerable to public misperceptions and to lampooning by the media.Not simply a book about current problems and future challenges, Failing the Future is rich with practical solutions and workable programs for change. Among her many insights, Kolodny offers a thorough defense of the role of tenure and outlines a new set of procedures to ensure its effective implementation; she proposes a structure for an "Antifeminist Intellectual Harassment Policy"; and she provides a checklist of family-sensitive policies universities can offer their staff, faculty, and administrators. Kolodny calls on union leaders, campus communities, policymakers, and the general public to work together in unprecedented partnerships. Her goal, as she states in a closing coda, is to initiate a revitalized conversation about public education.This book should be required reading for all those concerned with the future of higher education in this country-from college trustees to graduate students entering the professoriate, from faculty to university administrators, from officers of campus-based unions to education policymakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectiveszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxAdministration. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822396703zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822396703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822396703.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles